nt\"\n      ],\n      \"kwargs\": {\n        \"metadata\": {\n          \"source\": \"https://www.msn.com/en-in/health/other/best-wearables-to-buy-for-yourself-top-10-picks-for-you-to-adopt-a-wire-free-lifestyle/ar-BB1pMw8p\",\n          \"title\": \"MSN\",\n          \"language\": \"en-in\"\n        },\n        \"page_content\": \"\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nMSN\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\",\n        \"type\": \"Document\"\n      }\n    }\n  ],\n  [\n    {\n      \"lc\": 1,\n      \"type\": \"constructor\",\n      \"id\": [\n        \"langchain\",\n        \"schema\",\n        \"document\",\n        \"Document\"\n      ],\n      \"kwargs\": {\n        \"metadata\": {\n          \"source\": \"https://www.forbes.com/sites/emmakershaw/2024/07/16/los-angeles-hotel-figueroa-exhibit-features-immersive-ar-sculpture/\",\n          \"title\": \"Los Angeles' Hotel Figueroa Exhibit Features Immersive AR Sculpture\",\n          \"description\": \"Limitless by Leah Smithson is on display through February 2025 and features a one-of-a-kind interactive Augmented Reality sculpture.\",\n          \"language\": \"en\"\n        },\n        \"page_content\": \"Los Angeles' Hotel Figueroa Exhibit Features Immersive AR SculptureSubscribe To NewslettersBETAThis is a BETA experience. You may opt-out by\\u00a0clicking hereMore From ForbesJul 18, 2024,04:35pm EDTWhy Did Sol\\u2019s Lightsaber Change Color In \\u2018The Acolyte\\u2019 Finale?Jul 18, 2024,01:04pm EDT5 Of Joyce Lee\\u2019s Erotic Feminist Portraits Exploring The Female NudeJul 18, 2024,11:02am EDTKids Can Be Both Seen And Heard At Glamorous Ponte Vedra Inn & ClubJul 18, 2024,09:15am EDTBath & Body Works Launches \\u2018Stranger Things\\u2019 Candle CollectionJul 18, 2024,09:00am EDTPharrell Williams And Louis Vuitton Usher Timberland Boots Into LuxuryJul 18, 2024,07:53am EDTBook Celebrates Eileen Harris Norton\\u2019s Visionary Art Collecting Career, Amplifying Artists Of Color, Women And OthersJul 18, 2024,06:41am EDTHow Naomi Campbell Inspired BMW\\u2019s First High-Fashion CarJul 17, 2024,09:00am EDTBlack And POC Designers Find A Platform At Miami Swim Week: The ShowsEdit StoryForbesLifestyleArtsLos Angeles\\u2019 Hotel Figueroa Exhibit Features Immersive AR SculptureEmma KershawContributorOpinions expressed by Forbes Contributors are their own.Writer and editor covering arts and interior design.FollowingJul 16, 2024,08:15am EDTShare to FacebookShare to TwitterShare to LinkedinSoft Opaque Horizons by Los Angeles-based contemporary artist Leah Smithson.Leah Smithson\\nHotel Figueroa, a boutique five-star hotel located in Downtown Los Angeles, has long been a design-forward property from the moment you step inside. Artwork lines the walls of the lobby while themed suites captivate guests.\\n\\n\\nEach year, the hotel hosts an artist in residence, showcasing works from local artists. Leah Smithson, an L.A.-based multidisciplinary artist, is 2024\\u2019s featured creative. Her work has been displayed globally and she is part of of NEW INC, NEW MUSEUM\\u2019s incubator for art, design, and technology.\\n\\nSmithson\\u2019s exhibit at Hotel Figueroa is titled Limitless and celebrates the \\u201calchemy of invention.\\u201d A fully interactive experience, exhibit includes traditional paintings and an exclusive Augmented Reality sculpture \\u2014 a first for the hotel. Visitors and guests can interact with the immersive one-of-a-kind AR sculpture through their smartphones, tablets, and the new Apple Vision Pro, to launch a visual ASMR effect that tells the story of Smithson\\u2019s work.\\n\\n\\n\\u201cI explore the human condition using portraits that mirror an emotional state or frame of mind, rather than the likeness of a person. This work examines complex and emotional subjects objectively, leveraging both traditional\\u2014painting, ceramic sculpture\\u2014and new media\\u20143D animation, XR, architectural projection installation,\\u201d explained Smithson in a press release. \\u201cMy recent works incorporate images of avatars. Avatars, often generic in nature, transcend individual differences, so my recent works employ avatars as a tool to offer a glimpse into the collective human experience of love and loss. They remind us that even in the vastness of the world we live in, we are not alone.\\u201d\\n\\nTaking inspiration from the hotel\\u2019s rich history and honoring female innovators, Smithson worked with various materials to ensure an impactful exhibit. Foe example, for some of her paintings, she looked at the historical link between textiles and innovation and utilized canvas crafted from biodynamic cotton. This method reflected cotton breeder Sally Fox\\u2019s cultivation of naturally colored, organically grown cotton plants.\\nMORE FOR YOURNC Day 4: Trump Blasts Biden And \\u2018Crazy Nancy Pelosi\\u2019\\u2014Despite Promised \\u2018Unity\\u2019 ThemeGoogle Confirms Play Store App Deletion\\u2014Now Just 6 Weeks AwayEvery Big Name Urging Biden To Drop Out: Second Senator Goes PublicChimera by Leah Smithson.Leah Smithson\\n\\nRanging in size and shape from 22\\u201d x 25\\u201d to 52\\u201d x 64\\u201d, select pieces of Smithson\\u2019s works are available to the public for purchase. Prices start from $4,500 and include: Soft Opaque Horizons, oil and acrylic on Belgian linen, 36\\\" x 48\\\"; Chimera, oil and acrylic on Belgian linen, 24\\\" x 24\\\"; and Olga and Bath, oil and acrylic on canvas, 30\\u201d round.\\n\\n\\nElsewhere in the hotel, themed art classes help to inspire guests to unleash their creativity. In spring 2024, Hotel Figueroa hosted a series of exclusive ceramic classes in collaboration with L.A. design studio Two Faced Ceramics. Hosted by founder and ceramist Eve Palguta, the 16-person classes were an intimate, hands-on look into the world of ceramic homeware. Each class had a dedicated theme inspired by notable dates such as Women\\u2019s History Month and the Total Solar Eclipse, and guests were taught how to make jewelry dishes, mugs, and succulent holders.The lobby. Tanveer Badal\\nHotel Figueroa\\u2019s storied past is celebrated throughout the hotel. In 1926, the property was opened by the YMCA as a safe space for solo female travelers who, at the time, were disallowed from many hotels without a male chaperone. It was L.A.\\u2019s largest commercial building funded by women, for women.\\nLimitless is on display now through February 2025. No booking is required and entry is free.\\nFollow me on\\u00a0LinkedIn.\\u00a0Check out\\u00a0my\\u00a0website.\\u00a0Emma KershawFollowingEditorial StandardsPrintReprints & PermissionsJoin The ConversationComments\\u00a0One Community. Many Voices.\\u00a0Create a free account to share your thoughts.\\u00a0Read our community guidelines\\u00a0 here.Forbes Community GuidelinesOur community is about connecting people through open and thoughtful conversations. We want our readers to share their views and exchange ideas and facts in a safe space.In order to do so, please follow the posting rules in our site's\\u00a0Terms of Service.\\u00a0 We've summarized some of those key rules below. Simply put, keep it civil.Your post will be rejected if we notice that it seems to contain:False or intentionally out-of-context or misleading informationSpamInsults, profanity, incoherent, obscene or inflammatory language or threats of any kindAttacks on the identity of other commenters or the article's authorContent that otherwise violates our site's\\u00a0terms.User accounts will be blocked if we notice or believe that users are engaged in:Continuous attempts to re-post comments that have been previously moderated/rejectedRacist, sexist, homophobic or other discriminatory commentsAttempts or tactics that put the site security at riskActions that otherwise violate our site's\\u00a0terms.So, how can you be a power user?Stay on topic and share your insightsFeel free to be clear and thoughtful to get your point across\\u2018Like\\u2019 or \\u2018D